# Plotting the Data

Now that we imported our data, we can start visualizing it to better understand it. First, we can just call the function **mpt\_plot\(\)** in order to quickly draw up a graph of the Nyvquist Impedance graph.

```text
ex_mpt.mpt_plot()
```

![](.gitbook/assets/image%20%287%29.png)

## Graph Dimensions

We can change the dimensions of the graph by calling on **set\_new\_gph\_dims\(height, width\)** and customizing the size of the graph to our liking.

```text
#Say we want to make our graph 8 inches by 8 inches
ex_mpt.set_new_gph_dims(8,8)
ex_mpt.plot()
```

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Graph Window

We can not only change the size of the graph, but we can also customize the window of the graph we're looking at by calling on mpt plot, but this time, call out **x\_window = \[x\_min, x\_max\]** and **y\_window = \[y\_min, y\_max\]** and plant that into the plotting function.

```text
ex_mpt.mpt_plot(x_window = [0,5000], y_window = [0,5000])
```



![Notice how the boundary of the previous graph cut off at a little bit more than 6000!](data:image/png;base64,)

## Fitting and Residuals

There are also two attributes in mpt\_plot\(\) that can be called after the fitting process has been fitted. The first is the **fitting = 'on'** attribute, which allows the user to view the Nyvquist Impedance graph with the fitting equation layered on top of it. It is off if it is not called. There is also the residual attribute, denoted by **rr = 'on'** which can also be switched on and off by typing the state into the mpt\_plot\(\) function. The residual attribute plots the original graph, and also plots another graph with the residuals of the fitted equation and the actual graph.

```text
#Turn on fitting option
#ONLY WORKS AFTER FITTING THE GRAPH
ex_mpt.mpt_plot(fitting = 'on', rr = 'on')
```

![The top graph shows a fitted graph, and the bottom graph shows the residuals](.gitbook/assets/image%20%283%29.png)
